review_blob: While technically a wheat, its very clear, and is almost more lager than wheat. Wonderful cascade flavor. Ive had it in both bottle, and draft, and the bottle is much better. The hop profile seems to get lost on tap.
12oz bottle. Now I know Im not the only one that though it had a soapy aftertaste. A little too lemony, and also weak on carbonation. I just didnt like this one.

A very tasty, and easy drinking stout. If your a Guiness drinker who is looking for something more, then this is what you want. Just a bit of roast coffee flavor, but nothing overpowering. Great Cascade flavor and finish. small tan head, and great lacing. Definitely going to be a regular in my fridge!

2008 bottle: Freaking outsanding! Maybe a tad too hoppy, but still very good balance with the thick carmel malt sweetness. I think it would be almost perfect if the hops were down just a touch. Not a whole lot, but just a touch. Maybe get the IBUs down from 90 to the mid 70s and youd have a real winner. First Barleywine Ive tried so I dont have much to compare to, but definitely an overall favorite. Another great offering from Sierra Nevada.

On nitro tap at the brewpub. Overall this is my favorite Stout hands down to date. Complex yet smooth. Subtle notes of Coffee, Chocolate, slight raisin & malt sweetness, with more hop finish than the average stout. Very well balanced, with no single trait too overpowering. I need to find this in the bottle to see if it stands up to the draft offering at FFF.

I had  12oz bottle of 2007. $5.99 a bottlefrom Picadilly in Champaign. As I poured it into the glass, Motor Oil came to mind. Not 10W30 that comes out of the bottle, but the stuff that you drain out of the pan after its been in there for 5000 miles. The Bourbon and the alcohol burn, I can handle. What I couldnt get past was overwhelming taste of burnt prunes. Basically overpowered all the good qualities of the beer, and gave it a cough syrup quality. The other good flavors are there, you just have to look hard to find them. I would love to try one that has aged a little more to see if it balances out over time. On a side note after drinking half of the glass, I decided I wasnt really enjoying this anymore, so I dumped the remaining 6 oz into a 12 glass of Bass. Ended up with what was actually quite a fantastic, and still coal black stout.
